items.definition: The ANU Research School of Biology carries out research, research training,Â undergraduate and coursework Masters teaching in a wide range of biological and biomedical sciences. The School comprises three divisions: Biomedical Science and Biochemistry; Evolution, Ecology and Genetics; and Plant Sciences.

prefLabel._value: Research School of Biology (RSB), The Australian National University (ANU)

items.definition: The School of Archaeology and Anthropology combines five streams of social research and teaching — anthropology, archaeology, biological anthropology and the interdisciplinary fields of development studies and heritage and museum studies.

prefLabel._value: School of Archaeology and Anthropology, The Australian National University (ANU)

items.definition: The Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies (RSPAS) was originally founded in 1946, in 2010,  the RSPAS was reduced in status in line with other changes to other research schools across the ANU. Shortly afterwards a new College of Asia and the Pacific was established, which took over much of the work of the former RSPAS. (Courtesy of Wikipedia)

prefLabel._value: Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies (RSPAS), The Australian National University (ANU)

items.definition: The Research School of Asia and the Pacific (RSAP) is the institutional focus of the College of Asia and the Pacific's research efforts.

prefLabel._value: Research School of Asia and the Pacific (RSAP), The Australian National University (ANU)

items.definition: The Centre for Resource and Environmental Studies (CRES), was founded in 1973. CRES was combined with the School of Resources, Environment and Society (SRES) to form The Fenner School of Environment and Society in 2007. (Courtesy of Wikipedia)

prefLabel._value: Centre for Resource and Environmental Studies (CRES), The Australian National University (ANU)

items.definition: The Asia Pacific School of Economics and Government, is now incorporated as part of the Crawford School of Public Policy (CSPP).

prefLabel._value: Asia Pacific School of Economics and Government (APSEG), The Australian National University (ANU)

items.definition: The Crawford School of Public Policy is a graduate public policy school within the ANU College of Asia and the Pacific.

prefLabel._value: Crawford School of Public Policy (CSPP), The Australian National University (ANU)

items.definition: The Fenner School of Environment and Society brings together economists and hydrologists, historians and ecologists, foresters, geographers and climatologists to work together on the big environmental problems facing contemporary society.

prefLabel._value: Fenner School of Environment and Society, The Australian National University (ANU)

items.definition: iCAM (the Integrated Catchment Assessment and Management Centre) is a highly interdisciplinary research group consisting of social scientists, economists, hydrologists and interdisciplinary modellers.  iCAM’s mission is to develop and integrate the knowledge required to clarify management and policy options for sustaining vital water and related resources.

prefLabel._value: Integrated Catchment Assessment and Management Centre (iCAM), Fenner School of Environment and Society, The Australian National University (ANU)

items.definition: The North Australia Research Unit (NARU) was established in 1973 to specialise in research in north Australia and to provide a base and logistic support for Canberra-based members of The Australian National University (ANU) and members of other Australian and overseas institutions undertaking research in North Australia.

prefLabel._value: North Australia Research Unit (NARU), The Australian National University (ANU)
